*/
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Experiment:7
Illustrate the use of array of objects 
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Aim:
To illustrate the use of arrays of objects in C++, 
which are useful for storing and manipulating collections of similar entities efficiently using a single array structure.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Algorithm:
Define a class with attributes and member functions.
Declare an array of objects of this class.
Initialize the objects using a loop or individually.
Access members of the objects in the array using loop iteration.
Perform required operations such as display or compute using the array of objects.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
code:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Student {
    int id;
    float marks;

public:
    void assignValues(int x, float y) {
        id = x;
        marks = y;
    }

    void display() {
        cout << "ID: " << id << ", Marks: " << marks << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    Student s[3];  // Array of 3 Student objects

    // Assign values to each object in the array
    s[0].assignValues(101, 85.6);
    s[1].assignValues(102, 90.4);
    s[2].assignValues(103, 78.9);

    // Display the details of all students using the array of objects
    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
        s[i].display();
    }

    return 0;
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
output:
ID: 101, Marks: 85.6
ID: 102, Marks: 90.4
ID: 103, Marks: 78.9
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Result:
The program successfully demonstrates the use of an array of 
objects to manage and access multiple instances of a class efficiently.
Each object stores individual data, and the array structure allows handling them collectively for operations like assignment and display.
